\deflang1033\pard\par\plain\par\ql \par\ql \lang1033\ltrch\f6\fs40\b\i0\ul0\cf6\cb14\ 3\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\  \lang1033\ltrch\f2\fs36\b\i0\ul0\cf2\cb10\ Your navel is [like] a round basin\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\  Your navel is like a basin of clear water with which they wash, 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ and it [the basin] is made of marble, which in Arabic is called sahar. He compares it to a round basin 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ because the navel is shaped like a round hole. This praise does not refer to a womans beauty as the 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ above praise does, for [in] the above, her beloved praises her, but here, her companions praise her 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ about her deeds, saying: You are worthy to join us. The image symbolizes the Chamber of Hewn 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ Stone, which is situated in the navel of the world. \lang1033\ltrch\f2\fs36\b\i0\ul0\cf2\cb10\ where no mixed wine is lacking\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\  No beverage 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ will ever cease [to be found] there; he wishes to say that no words of instruction will cease or end 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ from there. \lang1033\ltrch\f2\fs36\b\i0\ul0\cf2\cb10\ your belly is [like] a stack of wheat\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\  which everyone needs. \lang1033\ltrch\f2\fs36\b\i0\ul0\cf2\cb10\ fenced in with roses\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\  fenced 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ and hedged about with roses. A light fence suffices her, and no one breaches it to enter. For example, 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ a bridegroom enters the nuptial canopy, his heart longing for the nuptials and for the love of his 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ marriage. When he comes to cohabit with her, she says to him, I have perceived a drop of blood like 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ [the size of] a mustard seed. He turns his face the other way. Now no snake bit him, nor did a 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ scorpion sting him. [Similarly,] one passes by on the road and sees freshly ripened fruit at the top of 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ the fig trees. He stretches out his hand to take [them]. They tell him, These belong to owners, and he 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ too withdraws his hand because of [the prohibition] of theft. This is the meaning of she is fenced in 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ with roses.  
\par \par }

