\deflang1033\pard\par\plain\par\ql \par\ql \lang1033\ltrch\f6\fs40\b\i0\ul0\cf6\cb14\ 5\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\  \lang1033\ltrch\f2\fs36\b\i0\ul0\cf2\cb10\ Your neck\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\  the Temple and the altar, which are erect and tall, and the Chamber of Hewn Stone, 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ which is also there, made for strength and for a shield, like an ivory tower. \lang1033\ltrch\f2\fs36\b\i0\ul0\cf2\cb10\ your eyes\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\  are like pools 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ (ברכות)\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\  in Heshbon, through which water flows. So are your eyes by the gate of the multitudes. Your 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ sages, when they sit in the gates of Jerusalem, the city of multitudes, and engage in the computation 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ (חשבון)\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\  of the seasons and the signs of the zodiactheir wisdom and understanding in the eyes of the 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ peoples flow like pools of water. Alternatively, we can explain \lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ ברכות בחשבון\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\  to mean doves, and this is 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ a Mishnaic usage: If one buys the doves of a dovecote, he must let the first brood \lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ (בריכה)\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\  fly away; 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ covedes in Old French, covey, brood. \lang1033\ltrch\f2\fs36\b\i0\ul0\cf2\cb10\ your face is as the tower of Lebanon\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\  Heb. \lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ אפך\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ . I cannot 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ explain this to mean a nose, either in reference to its simple meaning or in reference to its allegorical 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ meaning, for what praise of beauty is there in a nose that is large and erect as a tower? I say, therefore, 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ that \lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ אפך\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\  means a face. Now the reason he uses the singular and does not say \lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ אפיך\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ , is that he speaks 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ of the forehead, which is the main recognizable feature of the face, as it is said (Isa. 3:9): The 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ recognition of their faces testified against them. And you should know, for he progressively praises 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ them from bottom to topYour eyes are [like] pools in Heshbon, and after them the forehead, and 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ so do the nations praise (Ezek. 3:8): and your forehead is strong against the forehead of all who 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ come to harm you and entice you. \lang1033\ltrch\f2\fs36\b\i0\ul0\cf2\cb10\ as the tower of Lebanon, facing towards Damascus\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\  I saw [the 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ following] in the Midrash (Zuta): This is the house of the Lebanon forest, which King Solomon made. 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ Whoever stood on it could look and count how many houses there were in Damascus. Another 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ explanation: Your face looks towards Damascus; looks forward to the coming of the gates of 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ Jerusalem until Damascus, for it is destined to expand as far as Damascus.  
\par \par }

