\lang1033\ltrch\f2\fs36\b\i0\ul0\cf2\cb10\ head\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\  The braided hair of your Nazirites are as beautiful with commandments as braided purple 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ [ropes]. \lang1033\ltrch\f2\fs36\b\i0\ul0\cf2\cb10\ and the braided locks of your head\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\  Heb. \lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ ודלת ראשך\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ , because the braid is lifted up \lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ (מדלת)\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\  on 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ the highest part of the head. \lang1033\ltrch\f2\fs36\b\i0\ul0\cf2\cb10\ the king is bound in the tresses\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\  The name of the Omnipresent is bound 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ in the locks, as is stated (Num. 6:7): The crown of his God is on his head. \lang1033\ltrch\f2\fs36\b\i0\ul0\cf2\cb10\ tresses\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\  Heb. \lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ רהטים\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ , 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ courants in French; currents, windings [tresses]. This is what they call the fringes of the sashes, with 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ which they tie the girdles. Another explanation of \lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ מלך אסור ברהטים\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ : The Holy One, blessed be He, 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ is bound with love to the commandments and to the swiftness with which you run before Him.  
\par \par }

